<paragraph blockId="21.[813,1455,771,901]" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">
ORIGINAL DATA. — Three individuals attributed to the Giant Leaf-nosed Bat were captured during our field surveys. Two males (
<tableCitation box="[821,889,824,848]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="6.[134,145,230,248]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. — Sampling stations, habitat sampled and species captured during our field surveys (2016-2018). Abbreviations: A, above slow-flowing steam, B, cultivated farm; C, fallow farmland; D, beside fruiting tree; E, cleared farmland; F, understory of Primary forest; G, ecotone forest/alpine grassland, H, cave; I, gap between trees; J, forest fragment; K, waterhole." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF4C665DD54639431C8FFF45FDEA411C" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" tableUuid="DF4C665DD54639431C8FFF45FDEA411C">Table 1</tableCitation>
) were captured in a cultivated farm near a river at an altitude of 
<quantity box="[839,905,851,875]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" unit="m" value="470.0">470 m</quantity>
a.s.l. One female (
<tableCitation box="[1092,1166,851,875]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="6.[134,145,230,248]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. — Sampling stations, habitat sampled and species captured during our field surveys (2016-2018). Abbreviations: A, above slow-flowing steam, B, cultivated farm; C, fallow farmland; D, beside fruiting tree; E, cleared farmland; F, understory of Primary forest; G, ecotone forest/alpine grassland, H, cave; I, gap between trees; J, forest fragment; K, waterhole." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF4C665DD54639431C8FFF45FDEA411C" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" tableUuid="DF4C665DD54639431C8FFF45FDEA411C">Table 1</tableCitation>
) was also netted over a water hole in a primary forest at an altitude of 
<quantity box="[1209,1273,877,901]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.3" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" unit="m" value="630.0">630 m</quantity>
a.s.l.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="502" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="21.[813,1456,925,1267]" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">
HABITATS AND DISTRIBUTION. — This species is widely distributed in West Africa from 
<collectingCountry box="[1017,1090,951,975]" name="Senegal" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">Senegal</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[1125,1232,951,975]" name="Cameroon" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
, with a number of additional records further east to 
<collectingCountry box="[1128,1217,978,1002]" name="Tanzania" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
and south to 
<collectingCountry box="[1362,1451,978,1002]" name="Namibia" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">Namibia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[813,917,1004,1028]" name="Zimbabwe" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">Zimbabwe</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[964,1093,1004,1028]" name="Mozambique" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Monadjem" box="[1107,1322,1004,1028]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Monadjem" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" refId="ref28385" refString="MONADJEM A., TAYLOR P. J., COTTERILL F. P. D. &amp; SCHOEMAN M. C. 2010. - Bats of Southern and Central Africa: a Biogeographic and Taxonomic Synthesis. University of the Witwatersrand Press, Johannesburg, South Africa, 596 p. https: // doi. org / 10.1644 / 12 - MAMM-R- 184.1" type="book" year="2010">
Monadjem 
<emphasis box="[1221,1267,1004,1028]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">et al.</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
). This species generally inhabits lowland tropical rainforest (including secondary and riverine forest) and mesic savannah (
<bibRefCitation author="Monadjem" box="[1220,1441,1057,1081]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Monadjem" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" refId="ref28385" refString="MONADJEM A., TAYLOR P. J., COTTERILL F. P. D. &amp; SCHOEMAN M. C. 2010. - Bats of Southern and Central Africa: a Biogeographic and Taxonomic Synthesis. University of the Witwatersrand Press, Johannesburg, South Africa, 596 p. https: // doi. org / 10.1644 / 12 - MAMM-R- 184.1" type="book" year="2010">
Monadjem 
<emphasis box="[1335,1383,1057,1081]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">et al.</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
), where small colonies typically roost in caves, but occasionally could be found roosting in dense vegetation (
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[1265,1412,1110,1134]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" refId="ref25900" refString="HAPPOLD D. C. D. 1987. - The mammals of Nigeria. Clarendon Press. Oxford, 402 p. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0030605300027708" type="book" year="1987">Happold 1987</bibRefCitation>
). In Liberian Mount Nimba this species was captured in forested and disturbed habitats, ranging from 
<quantity box="[1124,1186,1163,1187]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" unit="m" value="460.0">460 m</quantity>
to 
<quantity box="[1215,1289,1163,1187]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.06" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" unit="m" value="1060.0">1060 m</quantity>
a.s.l. (
<bibRefCitation author="Monadjem" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Monadjem" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" pagination="359 - 375" refId="ref28330" refString="MONADJEM A., RICHARDS L. R. &amp; DENYS C. 2016. - An African bat hotspot: The exceptional importance of Mount Nimba for bat diversity. Acta Chiropterologica, 18 (2): 359 - 375. https: // doi. org / 10.3161 / 15081109 ACC 2016.18.2.005" type="journal article" year="2016">
Monadjem 
<emphasis box="[813,862,1189,1213]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[1075,1240,1189,1214]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" refId="ref25900" refString="HAPPOLD D. C. D. 1987. - The mammals of Nigeria. Clarendon Press. Oxford, 402 p. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0030605300027708" type="book" year="1987">Happold (1987)</bibRefCitation>
this species does not hunt daily, it preys mostly on large beetles and often return to the roosts to consume prey.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
